WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:17.290 --> 00:00:18.590
&gt;&gt; Matthew Barton: All right.

00:00:18.590 --> 00:00:19.890
Good afternoon.

00:00:19.890 --> 00:00:21.190
Welcome to the Library
of Congress.

00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:22.490
My name is Matthew Barton.

00:00:22.490 --> 00:00:25.330
I'm the Curator of the
Recorded Sounds section.

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:28.650
Most of the time, I'm down
at the National Audio Visual

00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:31.480
Conservation Center in
Culpepper, Virginia,

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:36.620
about 60 miles south,
oh, southwest of here.

00:00:36.620 --> 00:00:37.920
But, it's nice to get up here.

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:41.240
I used to work in this building,
though I get lost here now.

00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:45.130
Any time I get an audience here,
though, I like to ask who's here

00:00:45.130 --> 00:00:46.750
for the first time in
the Library of Congress.

00:00:46.750 --> 00:00:48.200
Anybody? Okay.

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:49.500
A few. Okay.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:50.850
Yeah. Welcome.

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:53.470
Please come back soon,
and don't be a stranger.

00:00:53.470 --> 00:00:55.890
It's here for you.

00:00:55.890 --> 00:01:02.920
So, this event, I
can't take much credit

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:04.470
for helping to put it together.

00:01:04.470 --> 00:01:09.310
It was very much the brain child
of Allison and Tony from the

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:10.610
from the Studs Terkel Archive,

00:01:10.610 --> 00:01:13.180
and I'll introduce
everybody in a moment.

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:17.110
I wanted to say something,
though, about the project

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:21.300
that we're working on with the
Studs Terkel Archive in Chicago.

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:25.240
This began a little
over seven years ago.

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:28.310
Studs Terkel's recorded
broadcast legacy amounts

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:32.790
to about 7000 reels
of tape over 45 years.

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:34.490
And, I'm not going to
go all technical on you,

00:01:34.490 --> 00:01:38.510
but I'll just say that as
a recorded sound archivist,

00:01:38.510 --> 00:01:41.020
that period of time
and that range

00:01:41.020 --> 00:01:44.370
of tape covers pretty much
all of the archival problems

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:47.540
that you can have with tape.

00:01:47.540 --> 00:01:49.990
But, boy, is it ever worth it.

00:01:49.990 --> 00:01:54.390
You know, and at this
point, we're about 70%

00:01:54.390 --> 00:01:55.910
through with the processing,

00:01:55.910 --> 00:01:59.890
and we're about 60%
digitally preserved.

00:01:59.890 --> 00:02:03.560
That is, 60% of those
7000 files,

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:06.350
over 4000 of them
have been digitized.

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:08.010
And, you can hear
them downstairs

00:02:08.010 --> 00:02:09.310
if you want to before you leave.

00:02:09.310 --> 00:02:13.370
Go down to LM119,
LM119 in this building.

00:02:13.370 --> 00:02:14.700
Karen Fishman our Head

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:19.070
of Reference should
be back there by then.

00:02:19.070 --> 00:02:21.890
[laughs] And, we'll set you
up with a pair of headphones,

00:02:21.890 --> 00:02:23.540
and you can listen
to Studs Terkel.

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:25.330
I particularly recommend
that you listen

00:02:25.330 --> 00:02:27.870
to Studs Terkel's
interview with Eliot Asinof,

00:02:27.870 --> 00:02:29.970
author of "Eight Men Out".

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:35.380
I just say a word
or two generally

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:36.820
about audio preservation.

00:02:36.820 --> 00:02:38.900
I kind of evangelize for it

00:02:38.900 --> 00:02:43.950
because I feel it's a neglected
research resource and, you know,

00:02:43.950 --> 00:02:47.620
just a neglected treasure,
countless treasures, really.

00:02:47.620 --> 00:02:53.670
And, I was fortunate enough
to know Studs Terkel slightly

00:02:53.670 --> 00:02:56.620
in that I worked for Alan Lomax,
one of his very good friends,

00:02:56.620 --> 00:03:00.170
and met Studs through
Alan and then later,

00:03:00.170 --> 00:03:03.390
after Alan had retired due
to a series of strokes,

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:06.880
the archive was on the same
floor of a building in New York

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:08.650
with Studs' publisher,
New Press.

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:11.340
And, Studs would visit
and always ask about Alan,

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:13.340
and one time, I actually
got to bring the two

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:14.930
of them together again.

00:03:14.930 --> 00:03:16.740
Really a lovely moment.

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:19.740
Alan had aphasia, had
difficulty speaking, but his,

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:21.720
the joy was just so palpable.

00:03:21.720 --> 00:03:26.020
It was really wonderful to be
together with the two of them.

00:03:26.020 --> 00:03:30.340
And, we're very fortunate
to have had Studs Terkel

00:03:30.340 --> 00:03:32.030
with us for so very long.

00:03:32.030 --> 00:03:34.830
We're very fortunate
that he saw fit

00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:37.660
to archive what he was
doing in the first place.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:38.960
Many people don't.

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:42.990
Even, no matter how seriously
they take their work in radio.

00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:44.290
It's an ephemeral thing.

00:03:44.290 --> 00:03:46.990
You finish with it, and
you're on to the next program.

00:03:46.990 --> 00:03:52.700
And, I brought with me, from
very late in Studs' life,

00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:54.390
"Touch and Go", this
wonderful memoir.

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:57.610
Got a very short passage to read
here, but it'll give you an idea

00:03:57.610 --> 00:04:01.050
of the things that are lost but
the things that can be saved.

00:04:01.050 --> 00:04:04.370
He's talking about the early
1950s when he's at a station,

00:04:04.370 --> 00:04:08.930
another Chicago station, not
WFMT where he [inaudible].

00:04:08.930 --> 00:04:12.820
And, he says, "I remember
interviewing Battling Nelson.

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.080
He was the lightweight
champion way back.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:18.510
We're talking about 1906 during
the San Francisco earthquake.

00:04:18.510 --> 00:04:20.990
He was there, giving money
to earthquake victims.

00:04:20.990 --> 00:04:24.330
A guy tips me off he's in
Chicago and where to find him.

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:29.050
Battling Nelson is in an seedy,
40 watt bulb Ontario Hotel room.

00:04:29.050 --> 00:04:31.110
I went with Hansen the engineer.

00:04:31.110 --> 00:04:33.570
Nelson's wife is cackling
as the old boy tries

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:36.980
to remember certain events
in his life, glory moments.

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:39.560
Old Bat has a tremendous
sheaf of papers and a ton

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:41.130
of scrapbooks, photos.

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:44.560
Nelson, the Durable Dane
and the King of Denmark,

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:47.300
etc. He opens it up,
and there are headlines.

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:49.270
And, he talks, and
there's his voice.

00:04:49.270 --> 00:04:51.790
Remember, he's from 1908, 1910,

00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:54.030
the kind of guy Hemingway
wrote about.

00:04:54.030 --> 00:04:57.100
After Red Quinlan left,
the new head dumped me.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:04:59.830
He did say, 'These tapes
are yours if you want them.'

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:01.460
I didn't take them.

00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:03.280
Should have.

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:07.020
Who else would, who the hell
else would have Battling

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:09.340
Nelson's voice today?"

00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:11.840
So, thankfully, we
don't have that voice,

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:13.460
but we have so many others.

00:05:13.460 --> 00:05:18.100
And, will you join me please in
welcoming this wonderful panel.

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:20.370
We have Alison Schein Holmes,

00:05:20.370 --> 00:05:23.110
archivist the Studs
Terkel Archive.

00:05:23.110 --> 00:05:26.000
Tony Macalus, Director
of the same archive.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.630
Derek Goldman, drama teacher
at Georgetown University.

00:05:30.630 --> 00:05:33.950
David Strathairn,
actor, Oscar nominee

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:35.670
and star of "Eight Men Out".

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:39.510
And, John Sayles, Director
of "Eight Men Out".

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:47.500
[ Applause ]

