But, first, we're going to
give you just a little more

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:03.080
background on this magnificent
thing called the Studs Terkel

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:04.380
Radio Archive.

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:06.150
And so, first of all, thank
you to the Library of Congress

00:06:06.150 --> 00:06:07.510
because this would
not be happening

00:06:07.510 --> 00:06:10.730
without all the amazing
digitizing.

00:06:10.730 --> 00:06:14.580
The archive is being managed
by Studs' old radio home WFMT

00:06:14.580 --> 00:06:18.170
in Chicago and the
Chicago History Museum

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:20.280
in a really special partnership.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:22.280
And, of course, we'd
also particularly want

00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:24.170
to think the National
Endowment for the Humanities

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:27.640
which has given really critical
support for this project

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:28.990
at a couple of key junctures.

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:33.620
And, especially give a call out
thanks to Jon Parrish Peede,

00:06:33.620 --> 00:06:36.100
the Chairman of NEH,
David Weinstein,

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:38.530
Program Officer who's
been a great source

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:40.130
of advice and wisdom.

00:06:40.130 --> 00:06:42.950
So, quickly, I'll tell you what
we've got planned for today.

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:44.250
We could go on into great detail

00:06:44.250 --> 00:06:45.890
into what is the Studs
Terkel Radio Archive.

00:06:45.890 --> 00:06:48.050
We're going to give you just a
little bit of that, but then,

00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:50.260
we're going to watch
come clips of Studs,

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:51.560
see a little bit
of "Eight Men Out".

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:54.720
Here's some readings, theatrical
brought to life, and a few clips

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:57.780
from Studs' program
specifically on baseball.

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:00.370
But, I'll mention, and
then my colleague, Allison,

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:03.400
will join to talk a little
more about what the archive is.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:05.170
But, essentially,
when Studs retired

00:07:05.170 --> 00:07:07.420
from his daily radio
show in 1997, again,

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:12.380
he left behind this trove of
tapes to Chicago History Museum.

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:14.940
The Library of Congress began
their work a little more

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:17.620
than a decade later, and
this History Museum came back

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:21.050
to Studs' old radio home,
now five years ago to say,

00:07:21.050 --> 00:07:22.510
"Do you have any thoughts on how

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:24.400
to make all this
accessible to the world?"

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:26.850
It's one thing to have
tapes even online,

00:07:26.850 --> 00:07:30.510
but how to make them appealing,
how to make a new generation

00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:31.960
of listeners want
to find out what's

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:33.370
in there and listen to them.

00:07:33.370 --> 00:07:36.180
And so, a long process
began, with help from the NEH

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:38.650
and others, of building
this site.

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:41.570
And then, just over a month and
a half ago, on Studs' birthday,

00:07:41.570 --> 00:07:45.230
May 16th, the whole thing
went live at studsterkel.org.

00:07:45.230 --> 00:07:47.480
And so, with beautiful
photography.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:49.840
There'll be a remixing
tool coming out soon

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:52.700
where people can go
in and remix audio,

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:54.760
but also education programs
we'll talk a bit more

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:56.060
about in a second.

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:58.800
A brand new podcast coming
out in October called

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:00.990
"Bug House Square"
with Eve Ewing,

00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:04.260
hosted by a phenomenal
young poet, scholar,

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:08.040
activist who will bring all
this to a new generation.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:10.900
But, today, we're here
specifically talking about Studs

00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:12.860
and baseball, and the
archive is divided

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:15.010
into about 60 categories,
and really,

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:17.760
we could do a similar event on
each one of those categories.

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.430
It could be Studs and
jazz or Studs and feminism

00:08:20.430 --> 00:08:22.860
or Studs and World War II.

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:24.370
But, today, we're
doing baseball,

00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:26.920
in part because of the fantastic
exhibit across the street,

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:29.200
which, if you haven't seen,
I definitely suggest going

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:30.500
over right after this.

00:08:30.500 --> 00:08:34.130
But, also, Studs was a
deep lover of baseball

00:08:34.130 --> 00:08:36.860
and all the cultural
surroundings of it,

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:41.090
the long conversation,
the understanding,

00:08:41.090 --> 00:08:44.130
the nuances of the game,
and one of the reasons

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:47.560
that he had this role in
John's film I think was

00:08:47.560 --> 00:08:49.470
because he was a
deep baseball lover.

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:52.200
But, I just to end my
portion and then bring Allison

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:54.010
up for a bit of this to
say that Studs, though,

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:55.530
when he was a kid,
didn't play baseball.

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:58.040
He was a, when he was in
Chicago, he actually was born

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:59.730
in New York but moved to
Chicago when he was eight.

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:02.260
And, he had asthma and
other health problems.

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:05.700
And so, he spent a couple of
summers in a kind of sanitarium

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:09.760
on Lake Michigan on the Michigan
side listening to the radio.

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:12.330
And, that's when he first
discovered politics and things

00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:15.150
like opera and other music,
sitting there in bed, you know,

00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:17.640
listening to things, listening
to baseball games as well,

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:23.720
listening to the Republican
Democratic convention in 1920.

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:27.270
And so, Studs, despite his love
of baseball, never really got

00:09:27.270 --> 00:09:31.180
to play baseball until
he was 90 years old.

00:09:31.180 --> 00:09:33.400
And, I'll tell you that story
at the end of the whole event.

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:34.700
But, you got to stick
around to find

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:38.290
out about Studs' major league
baseball debut at the age of 90.

