00:12:50.660 --> 00:12:52.680
And, as someone who's
been a, like, lifelong,

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:55.920
die hard baseball fan, it might
open up just to sort of put

00:12:55.920 --> 00:12:59.410
on the table a couple of themes
of, like, how, at least for me,

00:12:59.410 --> 00:13:01.540
and I felt like I
shared this with Studs,

00:13:01.540 --> 00:13:06.200
how the beautiful seriousness
of everything baseball.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:07.850
I'll put it that way.

00:13:07.850 --> 00:13:12.280
So, I was getting to know Studs
in the last decade of his life

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:13.950
in the '90s in Chicago.

00:13:13.950 --> 00:13:16.690
I'm a playwright and theater
maker and had the opportunity

00:13:16.690 --> 00:13:18.850
to write a play about
the Haymarket Riots

00:13:18.850 --> 00:13:21.610
at Steppenwolf Theatre,
and Studs was sort

00:13:21.610 --> 00:13:22.910
of introduced to Studs.

00:13:22.910 --> 00:13:27.370
And, he became the kind of
go to labor historian expert,

00:13:27.370 --> 00:13:29.590
you know, who couldn't have a
better person in the history

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:33.250
of the world, I felt to,
but I got to spend some time

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:35.510
with him getting to know him as
we were developing that play.

00:13:35.510 --> 00:13:38.870
And, that was an interesting
time in the baseball world

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:41.530
because it was the mid to late
'90s, and at least in Chicago,

00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:47.310
Sammy Sosa was, along with
Mark McGuire, informed,

00:13:47.310 --> 00:13:51.600
helped by various substances
as we now know and tarnished

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:55.700
by various substances
were shattering records.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:14:00.930
And, that was a big part of the
fodder for our time together

00:14:00.930 --> 00:14:05.910
and our conversations even in
that, in those early moments.

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:08.950
And, I remember him using
expressions like, you know,

00:14:08.950 --> 00:14:11.220
"Skilled craftsmen
plying their trade."

00:14:11.220 --> 00:14:12.940
You know, talking,
kind of, at that point,

00:14:12.940 --> 00:14:15.400
I think ironically
also in a certain way

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:17.720
about the way baseball
had changed.

00:14:17.720 --> 00:14:19.070
But, it was a source
of connection,

00:14:19.070 --> 00:14:22.550
and I grew up in Boston
very near Fenway Park

00:14:22.550 --> 00:14:25.110
as a lifelong, die
hard Red Sox fan.

00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:26.410
And, this was still the period

00:14:26.410 --> 00:14:30.030
where neither the Red Sox nor
the Cubs had broken their sort

00:14:30.030 --> 00:14:32.020
of almost century long curse.

00:14:32.020 --> 00:14:34.210
And, they were sort of,
as many of you know, very,

00:14:34.210 --> 00:14:38.170
kind of twined franchises
that had a kind of empathy

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:40.640
across the American and
the National League.

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:50.380
So, I ended up having the chance
to adapt and direct Studs' book

00:14:50.380 --> 00:14:54.270
"Will the Circle be Unbroken"
for, which deals with death

00:14:54.270 --> 00:14:56.760
and mortality and loss.

00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:58.420
And, we were developing

00:14:58.420 --> 00:15:03.980
that project a couple
years later in 2003.

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:06.970
And, if anyone remember
the 2003 baseball season,

00:15:06.970 --> 00:15:09.070
it was a particularly
interesting season

00:15:09.070 --> 00:15:11.180
to be thinking about the
chances of the Red Sox

00:15:11.180 --> 00:15:15.120
and the Cubs breaking
their respective curses.

00:15:15.120 --> 00:15:20.550
In fact, what happened
is in October in a sort

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:23.200
of painfully twinned symmetry,

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:27.950
the two teams were
both five outs away

00:15:27.950 --> 00:15:29.280
from making the World Series.

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:32.570
So, we spent a lot of that year
talking about the possibility

00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:35.070
of a Red Sox Cubs World
Series which was very real.

00:15:35.070 --> 00:15:39.320
They both had three run
leads with five outs away

00:15:39.320 --> 00:15:40.640
from making the World Series.

00:15:40.640 --> 00:15:42.490
And, neither team made it.

00:15:42.490 --> 00:15:46.460
The Cubs' probably
most infamous moment

00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:48.870
in franchise history
happened in game six

00:15:48.870 --> 00:15:52.130
when a fan named Steve Bartman
reached over and interfered

00:15:52.130 --> 00:15:56.860
with left fielder Moisés
Alou and opened the door

00:15:56.860 --> 00:15:59.870
for the Florida Marlins
to come back.

00:15:59.870 --> 00:16:02.470
And, for the Red Sox,
two nights later,

00:16:02.470 --> 00:16:08.030
manager Grady Little left Pedro
Martinez in longer than any,

00:16:08.030 --> 00:16:10.780
you know, as the whole Red Sox
nation screamed, "Take him out.

00:16:10.780 --> 00:16:12.080
Take him out.

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:13.380
He has nothing left."

00:16:13.380 --> 00:16:15.020
And, Little, at the time, said,

00:16:15.020 --> 00:16:17.160
"That's probably it
for me as a manager."

00:16:17.160 --> 00:16:20.090
And, of course, he was correct.

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:24.960
And, the Red Sox went on to lose
to the Yankees in game seven

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:28.640
when Aaron Boone, now the Red
Sox manager, hit a homerun off

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:30.210
of Tim Wakefield to send them

00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:32.990
against the Marlins
to the World Series.

00:16:32.990 --> 00:16:38.250
So, the following year, the Red
Sox actually broke the 86 year

00:16:38.250 --> 00:16:41.530
old curse, and in fact, just
symmetry that I think is,

00:16:41.530 --> 00:16:42.830
you know, whatever it means.

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:46.930
October 17, 2004 was the
first public performance

00:16:46.930 --> 00:16:49.640
of "Will the Circle be
Unbroken" at Steppenwolf Theatre

00:16:49.640 --> 00:16:51.200
which was a very moving occasion

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:53.150
with Studs there
and in attendance.

00:16:53.150 --> 00:16:58.150
And, it, as we entered the
party that night at the place

00:16:58.150 --> 00:16:59.700
where the post show party was,

00:16:59.700 --> 00:17:04.390
David Ortiz hit a 12th
inning homerun in game four

00:17:04.390 --> 00:17:07.050
against the Yankees which,
in what's now famously known

00:17:07.050 --> 00:17:09.250
by Red Sox as sort of
the Dave Roberts game.

00:17:09.250 --> 00:17:13.330
To sort of send the Red Sox
then won the next three games

00:17:13.330 --> 00:17:15.680
and went on to, it was the
first time a team had come back

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:18.100
from 3-0 to make
the World Series,

00:17:18.100 --> 00:17:20.110
and they won the
World Series in 2004.

00:17:20.110 --> 00:17:24.080
So, that's some of the, and
Studs and I, you know, we shared

00:17:24.080 --> 00:17:25.380
and talked about this.

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:27.860
We were living this
connected to that project.

00:17:27.860 --> 00:17:31.960
So, I'm going to just share a
couple of very quick thoughts

00:17:31.960 --> 00:17:34.930
that I think may resonate
through the theme of a couple

00:17:34.930 --> 00:17:38.200
of the readings that David and
I have picked from the sort

00:17:38.200 --> 00:17:42.890
of [inaudible] of Studs things
that you'll hear that feel to me

00:17:42.890 --> 00:17:48.140
like they speak to why I feel
like my love and reverence

00:17:48.140 --> 00:17:50.850
for Studs Terkel is
so tied to my love

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:53.100
and feelings about baseball.

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:56.740
Tony eluded to one thing already
which is maybe the most obvious

00:17:56.740 --> 00:18:00.570
which is that baseball is truly
a conversationalists game.

00:18:00.570 --> 00:18:04.060
The role of the vernacular
and of the, you know,

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:07.070
from the vendors to the
kind of rhythm of the game

00:18:07.070 --> 00:18:09.700
and the way it opens
conversation.

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:12.350
The nicknames that have
existed across time.

00:18:12.350 --> 00:18:13.760
I just think it's just
like there's something

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:18.050
about the oral nature of the
game the fans' role in that

00:18:18.050 --> 00:18:21.520
and the relationship to time
that's unique to baseball.

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:24.860
Another thing that Studs,
it's a theme that comes

00:18:24.860 --> 00:18:26.380
out a little bit in what
we're going to hear,

00:18:26.380 --> 00:18:29.530
but I think it's very deeply
Studs is baseball has a really

00:18:29.530 --> 00:18:32.720
interesting relationship
between success and failure.

00:18:32.720 --> 00:18:37.100
It's the best teams, you know,

00:18:37.100 --> 00:18:40.350
the sort of adage is every
team loses 50 to 60 games

00:18:40.350 --> 00:18:42.400
and every team wins
50 to 60 games.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:44.800
And, it's what teams do
with the other 40 games

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:50.620
that distinguishes, you know,
the best from the worst.

00:18:50.620 --> 00:18:54.670
And, similarly, you know, a
300 hitter is a great hitter

00:18:54.670 --> 00:18:56.550
and succeeds 30% of the time.

00:18:56.550 --> 00:18:58.200
And, a 200 hitter
is a terrible hitter

00:18:58.200 --> 00:18:59.910
and succeeds 20% of the time.

00:18:59.910 --> 00:19:01.210
You know, more or less.

00:19:01.210 --> 00:19:03.650
So, I think that's actually
really something that Studs,

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:09.050
there's something about the idea
that, like, everybody fails,

00:19:09.050 --> 00:19:10.400
and everybody succeeds.

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:13.930
And, people, and the sort of,
and there's a lot of both.

00:19:13.930 --> 00:19:17.640
And, you get different turns
to bat, in a sense kind

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:19.950
of that feels like something

00:19:19.950 --> 00:19:23.160
that connects people
to baseball.

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:27.190
Studs, as everyone, I think,
knows, was a huge aficionado

00:19:27.190 --> 00:19:30.430
of music, and his work
itself is hugely musical

00:19:30.430 --> 00:19:32.090
and attuned to music.

00:19:32.090 --> 00:19:34.660
And, a lot of the
credit for that goes

00:19:34.660 --> 00:19:35.960
to amazing people he worked

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:38.730
with like the incredible editor
Sydney Lewis, like the sort

00:19:38.730 --> 00:19:43.920
of sense of musicality of
the human voice and structure

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:47.090
and improvisation and
relationship to jazz.

00:19:47.090 --> 00:19:50.540
And, I think even the, that's
when I was thinking the books

00:19:50.540 --> 00:19:52.300
that there's sort of, there's
something, a way of thinking

00:19:52.300 --> 00:19:54.740
about the passages is
almost like innings

00:19:54.740 --> 00:19:56.040
in a certain kind of way.

00:19:56.040 --> 00:20:00.150
So, I think we could go on,
and you'll pluck other themes.

00:20:00.150 --> 00:20:04.850
But, I wanted to sort of begin
by sharing some of how, for me,

00:20:04.850 --> 00:20:06.700
and this is part of why it
feels really special to be here.

00:20:06.700 --> 00:20:09.750
These things all feel like
they get to the deepest core

00:20:09.750 --> 00:20:11.370
of what I love about Studs.

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:14.360
So, I'm going to hand it
over to David who's going

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:17.160
to read a couple passages over
the course of our time together,

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:22.060
but this first one sort
of begins talking about,

00:20:22.060 --> 00:20:27.770
it's Studs talking about his
relationship to famous owner,

00:20:27.770 --> 00:20:30.800
baseball owner of the
Chicago White Sox, Bill Veeck.

00:20:32.820 --> 00:20:34.820
&gt;&gt; David Strathairn: To
me, Bill Veeck was the last

00:20:34.820 --> 00:20:39.770
of the independent spirits in
sports, and certainly baseball.

00:20:39.770 --> 00:20:43.900
Before he died, we were sitting
at Miller's Pub in Chicago,

00:20:43.900 --> 00:20:45.530
and he would say, "We're gone.

00:20:45.530 --> 00:20:47.280
It's corporate America."

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:49.410
And, he was referring to
the Steinbrenners and,

00:20:49.410 --> 00:20:53.200
etc. Corporate America
is taking over.

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:56.750
It's not as personal as it was.

00:20:56.750 --> 00:21:01.290
What I love about Bill Veeck is
the way he analyzed baseball.

00:21:01.290 --> 00:21:03.900
He say, "You know, we
are a country of losers

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:08.690
to a great extent, but certain
moments, we experience victory.

00:21:08.690 --> 00:21:11.130
Let's savor that."

00:21:11.130 --> 00:21:14.740
For example, the
exploding scoreboard.

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:16.520
A corny thing.

00:21:16.520 --> 00:21:20.050
And Comiskey Park when he was
General Manager of the Sox.

00:21:20.050 --> 00:21:24.630
The electric scoreboard,
and the team was horrible.

00:21:24.630 --> 00:21:28.340
The team was rotten, but the
home team gets a homerun,

00:21:28.340 --> 00:21:29.670
and the crowd goes crazy.

00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:32.090
He got that from
William Saroyan's play,

00:21:32.090 --> 00:21:33.390
"The Time of Your Life."

00:21:33.390 --> 00:21:34.690
It's about the depression.

00:21:34.690 --> 00:21:36.420
There's a bar in San Francisco.

00:21:36.420 --> 00:21:38.270
All the losers are there.

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:41.020
Now, there's a kid
playing a pinball machine.

00:21:41.020 --> 00:21:42.860
He never wins.

00:21:42.860 --> 00:21:45.810
One day, he hits the jackpot,
and the pinball machine.

00:21:45.810 --> 00:21:47.110
The flags go up.

00:21:47.110 --> 00:21:50.400
The band plays Dixie,
and it's glorious.

00:21:50.400 --> 00:21:52.410
That's the electric scoreboard.

00:21:52.410 --> 00:21:55.970
The losers can enjoy
a moment of triumph.

00:21:55.970 --> 00:21:59.670
He believed in that very much.

00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:03.750
The Chicago White Sox were a
blue collar team, south side,

00:22:03.750 --> 00:22:06.430
steel mills, Irish
to great extent.

00:22:06.430 --> 00:22:08.680
It was the park of losers.

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:14.370
Ever since the Black Sox,
Joe Jackson and the others.

00:22:14.370 --> 00:22:18.690
Now, why Babe Ruth is
the greatest athlete.

00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:21.210
Well, first of all, it's
from my vantage point.

00:22:21.210 --> 00:22:25.100
I'm 86 as we have this
conversation, going on 87.

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:27.750
So, naturally, a certain
period of my life,

00:22:27.750 --> 00:22:31.270
the period of the 1930s, and
for that matter the '20s,

00:22:31.270 --> 00:22:34.820
I was a kid, a young man.

00:22:34.820 --> 00:22:37.970
It was The Babe who
saved baseball.

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:40.320
Remember that, the
Black Sox scandal?

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:43.970
That was it for baseball, and
then they bring in that phony,

00:22:43.970 --> 00:22:46.440
the Commissioner K.M. Landis.

00:22:46.440 --> 00:22:49.800
And, they punished the ones
up front, the ball players.

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:51.790
And, of course, you
exonerate the others

00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:55.960
who are really responsible and
who made these guys culpable.

00:22:55.960 --> 00:22:58.600
So, there's baseball
in terrible form,

00:22:58.600 --> 00:23:02.420
and along comes this Paul
Bunyan-esque figure, this guy,

00:23:02.420 --> 00:23:08.260
this man child, The Babe, George
Herman Ruth, the Sultan of Swat.

00:23:08.260 --> 00:23:10.780
Bang. And, you see him
circling those bases

00:23:10.780 --> 00:23:15.750
with the skinny delicate legs
tripping, almost feminine like.

00:23:16.860 --> 00:23:20.340
We know off the field, he
was quite a colorful figure.

00:23:20.340 --> 00:23:23.970
He had a gargantuan appetite
in every aspect of life,

00:23:23.970 --> 00:23:26.290
but The Babe represented,

00:23:26.290 --> 00:23:29.700
the word is eponymous,
more than synonymous.

00:23:29.700 --> 00:23:34.300
When you say "baseball" you
say Babe Ruth, of course.

00:23:34.300 --> 00:23:38.890
The World Series at Cubs
field, and they're booing him.

00:23:38.890 --> 00:23:41.780
He's facing Cubs
pitcher Charlie Root.

00:23:41.780 --> 00:23:43.230
Now, here comes the story.

00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:47.430
Now, everybody in know
says they saw the game.

00:23:47.430 --> 00:23:49.990
That means the place could
have seated a million people.

00:23:49.990 --> 00:23:51.460
You've heard this many times.

00:23:51.460 --> 00:23:54.060
I saw that game.

00:23:54.060 --> 00:23:58.760
Some point towards center field,
some point toward right field.

00:23:58.760 --> 00:24:00.890
Apparently, he did
point somewhere,

00:24:00.890 --> 00:24:03.810
and he hit the ball
where he pointed.

00:24:03.810 --> 00:24:06.910
That seems to be the truth, and
I could lie and say, of course,

00:24:06.910 --> 00:24:10.480
I was one of the million who
was at Cubs Park that day.

00:24:10.480 --> 00:24:13.770
Invariably, you'll find fans who
create a moment they've heard

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:15.920
about and they want to
be part of it again.

00:24:15.920 --> 00:24:18.510
Well, again, we're losers,

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:22.090
so it's a natural
logic that I was there.

00:24:22.090 --> 00:24:26.270
And, you half believe them.

00:24:26.270 --> 00:24:28.140
Wait until next year.

00:24:28.140 --> 00:24:31.150
The phrase of all sportscasters.

00:24:31.150 --> 00:24:34.600
It's waiting for Godot in a way.

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:39.170
The Chicagoans are Vladimir
and Estragon, Deedee and Gogo,

00:24:39.170 --> 00:24:42.230
the two tramps rolled
into one, the two heroes

00:24:42.230 --> 00:24:44.440
of Samuel Beckett's play.

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:47.760
We are waiting for
Godot, waiting forever,

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:50.560
but at least there's hope.

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:52.510
That, in a sense, is Chicago.

