really far apart and kind

00:37:48.270 --> 00:37:49.570
of come down to Studs' level.

00:37:49.570 --> 00:37:52.230
When we had to walk together,
we just had to widen the lens.

00:37:52.230 --> 00:37:55.440
And, when I, and I also knew

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:58.060
that Studs had been a
buddy of Bill Veecks.

00:37:58.060 --> 00:38:02.840
And so, I figure, well, he must
be, you know, a Cubs fan by now.

00:38:02.840 --> 00:38:06.310
You know, and he's interviewed
all these baseball guys.

00:38:06.310 --> 00:38:07.610
So, Stud say, "Oh, yeah.

00:38:07.610 --> 00:38:08.910
Hugh Fullerton.

00:38:08.910 --> 00:38:10.210
I knew that, you know.

00:38:10.210 --> 00:38:11.570
And, I was around
for the Black Sox.

00:38:11.570 --> 00:38:16.130
And, it was like a pall over
Chicago, this awful history."

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:19.300
And then, he got into
Kenesaw Mountain Landis

00:38:19.300 --> 00:38:21.200
and how he put the
wrong people in jail.

00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:23.450
And then, he ended up,
you know, being the czar

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:26.630
of baseball forever
in equity of that.

00:38:26.630 --> 00:38:30.570
So, the first day that
Studs was on the set,

00:38:30.570 --> 00:38:32.850
he was telling stories and
everything, and you know,

00:38:32.850 --> 00:38:35.050
he had a great mind for
his lines and everything.

00:38:35.050 --> 00:38:36.870
No problem with the lines.

00:38:36.870 --> 00:38:39.500
The real problem was when
he would finish his lines,

00:38:39.500 --> 00:38:43.600
he'd freeze with
cigar in midair.

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:45.170
And then, wait for another line.

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:47.390
And then, he'd say his
line, and he'd freeze.

00:38:47.390 --> 00:38:50.770
I said, "Studs, this
isn't radio."

00:38:50.770 --> 00:38:53.130
"Oh, god. That's right,
that's not radio."

00:38:53.130 --> 00:38:56.520
Because he had, as a young
man, done radio plays.

00:38:56.520 --> 00:38:59.500
And, he said, "I always got
the Edward G. Robinson part,

00:38:59.500 --> 00:39:02.080
and I always got to hold the
cigar and say, 'Yeah, yeah.'"

00:39:02.080 --> 00:39:04.140
[ Laughter ]

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:06.430
And, it actually took
them very many takes,

00:39:06.430 --> 00:39:08.560
and I had to remind
him many, many times,

00:39:08.560 --> 00:39:10.600
you know, this is not radio.

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:12.990
You have to, like,
pretend you're listening

00:39:12.990 --> 00:39:14.290
to the other people even

00:39:14.290 --> 00:39:18.810
if you're really just
looking for your next line.

00:39:18.810 --> 00:39:21.350
And, the, I did a show
a couple more times.

00:39:21.350 --> 00:39:24.590
He did a novel, "Union
Dues" that I had done.

00:39:24.590 --> 00:39:27.140
And, I came in, and I
figured, well, okay.

00:39:27.140 --> 00:39:29.640
It's a long book, and I'm
sure he has researchers

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:30.940
and everything.

00:39:30.940 --> 00:39:33.850
And, I sit down with him,
and there are probably

00:39:33.850 --> 00:39:38.990
in a 375 page book,
there's 100 little markers.

00:39:38.990 --> 00:39:41.220
He's annotated my book.

00:39:41.220 --> 00:39:42.520
And so, as we're going through,

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:45.770
and he's color coded
the annotations.

00:39:45.770 --> 00:39:48.040
So, the red ones are the
first ones to get to.

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:50.750
And, I mean, just amazing.

00:39:50.750 --> 00:39:53.000
And, so comfortable
in the conversation.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:57.300
There's no "ums" and "ers",
but he was this magician

00:39:57.300 --> 00:39:58.600
at drawing people out.

00:39:58.600 --> 00:40:02.470
And, he knew kind of where
he wanted to take you,

00:40:02.470 --> 00:40:04.340
where he wanted you
to lead the audience

00:40:04.340 --> 00:40:08.070
to to reveal yourself,
to reveal the book.

00:40:08.070 --> 00:40:12.220
One of the things in the
archive is his interview

00:40:12.220 --> 00:40:13.520
with Eliot Asinof.

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:21.420
Eliot Asinof was, he'd been
a minor league ball player.

00:40:21.420 --> 00:40:25.470
He basically, because he wasn't
great and because he was Jewish,

00:40:25.470 --> 00:40:28.190
he didn't get to, and World War
II came around, he didn't get

00:40:28.190 --> 00:40:29.560
to be a major league
ball player.

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:33.480
But, he probably could have hung
on if he hadn't been Jewish.

00:40:33.480 --> 00:40:35.900
He got black listed.

00:40:35.900 --> 00:40:40.520
Eventually, he found that
his name showed up first

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:45.250
when he got his, you
know, his, you know,

00:40:45.250 --> 00:40:48.830
much redacted stuff
from the FBI.

00:40:48.830 --> 00:40:50.870
His first appearance
on their list was

00:40:50.870 --> 00:40:52.880
for signing a petition outside

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:55.420
of Yankee Stadium saying
it was time for them

00:40:55.420 --> 00:40:57.100
to have a black ball player.

00:40:57.100 --> 00:41:00.190
That got you on J. Edgar
Hoover's shit list at that time.

00:41:00.190 --> 00:41:03.340
And then, he married
Marlon Brando's sister,

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:08.110
and she got black listed,
basically, as a, you know,

00:41:08.110 --> 00:41:11.920
a diversion so they wouldn't
go after her brother.

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:14.500
And, pretty soon,
he was black listed.

00:41:14.500 --> 00:41:21.020
And, he started tracking
down these baseball players,

00:41:21.020 --> 00:41:23.520
and he talked to these
guys just before they died,

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:25.000
many of them just
before they died.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.320
And, they all had their
own version of the thing,

00:41:27.320 --> 00:41:31.630
but he wrote this, you know, and
Nelson Algren was kind of one

00:41:31.630 --> 00:41:33.860
of the people who got
him started on it.

00:41:33.860 --> 00:41:37.850
But, their talk is
an incredible one.

00:41:37.850 --> 00:41:42.510
His nickname among his writer
friends was "God's angry man".

00:41:42.510 --> 00:41:45.040
[ Laughter ]

00:41:45.040 --> 00:41:47.830
And, he was late in the
black list, so he was a front

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:49.970
for a couple years
for other guys

00:41:49.970 --> 00:41:51.910
who had already been
black listed.

00:41:51.910 --> 00:41:54.700
Except he was so cantankerous.

00:41:54.700 --> 00:41:57.150
He went in for one writer,

00:41:57.150 --> 00:41:59.200
and he started arguing
with the producer.

00:41:59.200 --> 00:42:02.290
Those are the stupidest notes
I've ever seen and got fired.

00:42:02.290 --> 00:42:06.700
When it wasn't even his project.

00:42:06.700 --> 00:42:11.130
And, Studs was kind of the
benign version of, you know,

00:42:11.130 --> 00:42:13.340
they had this very similar past.

00:42:13.340 --> 00:42:14.680
And, Studs was kind
of the benign,

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:16.300
who could get along
with anybody.

00:42:16.300 --> 00:42:19.080
And, Eliot was the guy
who would find a way

00:42:19.080 --> 00:42:21.740
to start a war with
almost anybody.

00:42:21.740 --> 00:42:26.100
&gt;&gt; David Strathairn: I just
