So, there were about 300 people
in left field, and they had two,

00:49:39.770 --> 00:49:41.930
you know, ushers holding a rope

00:49:41.930 --> 00:49:44.100
to keep them back
against the wall.

00:49:44.100 --> 00:49:46.380
And so, of course,
when, you know,

00:49:46.380 --> 00:49:49.190
it was a ground rule double
if you hit into that area,

00:49:49.190 --> 00:49:51.900
so of course, a Chicago
guy hit a fly ball there,

00:49:51.900 --> 00:49:54.630
they would push forward
and bring the wall in.

00:49:54.630 --> 00:49:57.950
And, when a Cincinnati guy
hit one, they would back

00:49:57.950 --> 00:50:01.350
up against the wall and give
their guy a chance to catch it.

00:50:01.350 --> 00:50:04.830
So, it was a much more
personal kind of thing.

00:50:04.830 --> 00:50:08.140
And, you were talking to
guys throughout the game.

00:50:08.140 --> 00:50:12.350
They were, they were,
there was no hiding them.

00:50:12.350 --> 00:50:14.000
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus: So, we're going
to look at just a little clip

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.680
from the film, and then
another reading and.

00:50:16.680 --> 00:50:17.980
&gt;&gt; Allison Schein Holmes:
[inaudible] find the clip.

00:50:17.980 --> 00:50:19.280
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus: Okay.

00:50:19.280 --> 00:50:20.580
&gt;&gt; Allison Schein Holmes: Sorry.

00:50:20.580 --> 00:50:21.880
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus: We will.

00:50:21.880 --> 00:50:23.900
So, let's go on to the
last reading there,

00:50:23.900 --> 00:50:25.630
and then we'll bring the
clip up if we find it.

00:50:25.630 --> 00:50:27.220
And then, hear a
little more Studs.

00:50:27.220 --> 00:50:28.840
But then, we want
to open things up

00:50:28.840 --> 00:50:30.540
and get questions
from you all as well.

00:50:30.540 --> 00:50:32.840
So, anything you
want to say there?

00:50:32.840 --> 00:50:35.380
&gt;&gt; Derek Goldman: Do you want to
do that just a thought on the.

00:50:35.380 --> 00:50:36.680
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus: Yeah.

00:50:36.680 --> 00:50:37.980
&gt;&gt; Derek Goldman: Do
you want to, should we,

00:50:37.980 --> 00:50:39.280
do we have the audio Roger
Kahn Jackie Robinson?

00:50:39.280 --> 00:50:41.090
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:50:41.090 --> 00:50:42.390
Why don't we do that
before the reading,

00:50:42.390 --> 00:50:43.690
and then we can open it up if.

00:50:43.690 --> 00:50:44.990
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus: Okay.

00:50:44.990 --> 00:50:46.290
That sounds good.

00:50:46.290 --> 00:50:48.330
So, this is [inaudible]
Roger Kahn talking

00:50:48.330 --> 00:50:50.060
about Jackie Robinson.

00:50:50.060 --> 00:50:51.360
What more can you say?

00:50:51.360 --> 00:50:55.330
&gt;&gt; It's a book about certain men
who happen in the glory moments

00:50:55.330 --> 00:50:58.470
of their lives to have
been baseball players.

00:50:58.470 --> 00:51:01.580
It's about skilled
craftsmen at a certain moment

00:51:01.580 --> 00:51:04.790
in their lives how it happened
to them after the skill had gone

00:51:04.790 --> 00:51:06.190
and the glory had gone.

00:51:06.190 --> 00:51:07.490
So, what happens as humans.

00:51:07.490 --> 00:51:10.340
But, certain people
together at a certain moment.

00:51:10.340 --> 00:51:11.640
And, you said integrated.

00:51:11.640 --> 00:51:15.950
So, now, the catalytic figure
here is Jackie Robinson.

00:51:15.950 --> 00:51:19.900
&gt;&gt; Jackie's just the tremendous
man and overlooked now,

00:51:19.900 --> 00:51:21.200
I think, generally by society.

00:51:21.200 --> 00:51:22.630
People forget.

00:51:22.630 --> 00:51:25.820
Let me say some of the things
that Jackie had endured

00:51:25.820 --> 00:51:27.730
within the bound of taste.

00:51:27.730 --> 00:51:30.730
This is the 25th anniversary,

00:51:30.730 --> 00:51:32.800
this Opening Day will
be the 25th anniversary

00:51:32.800 --> 00:51:35.320
of Jackie Robinson's first
game in the major leagues.

00:51:35.320 --> 00:51:36.840
His black cat was loose.

00:51:36.840 --> 00:51:39.290
&gt;&gt; 1947.

00:51:39.290 --> 00:51:41.740
&gt;&gt; 1947, Opening Day.

00:51:41.740 --> 00:51:44.200
He went hitless.

00:51:44.200 --> 00:51:48.370
A black cat was loosed on the
field, and Jack walked over

00:51:48.370 --> 00:51:51.630
and picked up the animal
and stroked its fur.

00:51:52.720 --> 00:51:57.160
Watermelon, shoes were held
up, and they shine these.

00:51:57.160 --> 00:51:59.350
He went up to bat in St.
Louis, and somebody said,

00:51:59.350 --> 00:52:01.400
"No wonder you can't
get a decent shine

00:52:01.400 --> 00:52:03.400
in St. Louis anymore."

00:52:03.400 --> 00:52:05.240
John Kiren [assumed spelling]
described this as the subtle wit

00:52:05.240 --> 00:52:06.870
so characteristic
of ball players

00:52:06.870 --> 00:52:08.370
with some irony years ago.

00:52:08.370 --> 00:52:10.930
The Cardinals were
going to strike.

00:52:10.930 --> 00:52:13.710
The strike was broken by
enterprising newspaper work.

00:52:13.710 --> 00:52:16.740
The Dodgers themselves
petitioned,

00:52:16.740 --> 00:52:19.600
and we were not talking then
about scatter site housing,

00:52:19.600 --> 00:52:21.520
about integrated
schools, about anything.

00:52:21.520 --> 00:52:24.730
We were talking about the right
of a man to play in the infield

00:52:24.730 --> 00:52:26.030
of a major league baseball team.

00:52:26.030 --> 00:52:28.990
And, I think it's probably
hard for young people

00:52:28.990 --> 00:52:31.900
to realize what a
flaming issue this was.

00:52:31.900 --> 00:52:34.310
And so, as the times
have changed,

00:52:34.310 --> 00:52:36.640
and Jack is a republican.

00:52:36.640 --> 00:52:40.110
He seems conservative
to many young militants.

00:52:40.110 --> 00:52:42.540
Works for Nelson
Rockefeller on occasion.

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:44.830
And, I said to him, one
day we were having lunch.

00:52:44.830 --> 00:52:47.990
I said, "Jack, you know,
you've become conservative."

00:52:47.990 --> 00:52:50.190
And, he said, "I have
not become conservative.

00:52:50.190 --> 00:52:52.650
I'm exactly what I
was, what I always was,

00:52:52.650 --> 00:52:54.400
but the times have
changed around me."

00:52:54.400 --> 00:52:55.700
&gt;&gt; That's interesting, though,

00:52:55.700 --> 00:52:58.530
the young today Jackie
Robinson conservative.

00:52:58.530 --> 00:53:01.120
The young militants look upon
him as somewhat of a Tom.

00:53:01.120 --> 00:53:03.190
Yet, forgetting what he did

00:53:03.190 --> 00:53:04.490
because it's kind
of [inaudible].

00:53:04.490 --> 00:53:06.710
But, the same thing, he's saying

00:53:06.710 --> 00:53:08.900
that times have altered
considerably you see.

00:53:08.900 --> 00:53:13.700
All he was is this man who was a
conservative politically wanted

00:53:13.700 --> 00:53:15.450
to follow his craft.

00:53:15.450 --> 00:53:18.410
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus: Great.

00:53:18.410 --> 00:53:20.680
&gt;&gt; Matthew Barton: If I could.

00:53:20.680 --> 00:53:21.980
&gt;&gt; Derek Goldman: Yeah, please.

00:53:21.980 --> 00:53:23.280
Hi. Yeah.

00:53:23.280 --> 00:53:24.790
&gt;&gt; Matthew Barton: The
sound archivist in me,

00:53:24.790 --> 00:53:27.020
just going to break
continuity for a moment

00:53:27.020 --> 00:53:28.760
and go back to Lawrence Ritter.

00:53:28.760 --> 00:53:31.200
I suspect most of you know
who Lawrence Ritter was

00:53:31.200 --> 00:53:33.680
and what he did, but I just
wanted to make sure for anyone

00:53:33.680 --> 00:53:36.420
who doesn't because
it's really singular.

00:53:36.420 --> 00:53:40.530
In the early '60s, I think, he
went around and interviewed,

00:53:40.530 --> 00:53:44.320
recorded interviews with as
many early baseball players

00:53:44.320 --> 00:53:45.890
as he could find.

00:53:45.890 --> 00:53:48.290
And, this became the basis
of his book "The Glory

00:53:48.290 --> 00:53:50.840
of Their Times" which
is a marvelous book.

00:53:50.840 --> 00:53:53.740
And, those recordings,
you know, thankfully,

00:53:53.740 --> 00:53:55.040
and this is the archivist
speaking.

00:53:55.040 --> 00:53:57.250
And, those are recordings,
thankfully,

00:53:57.250 --> 00:53:58.550
that have been archived.

00:53:58.550 --> 00:53:59.850
They all survived.

00:53:59.850 --> 00:54:02.290
There was even a record album
that came out in the '60s,

00:54:02.290 --> 00:54:05.380
and you can probably find
some of these things online.

00:54:05.380 --> 00:54:08.230
So, a plug for Lawrence
Ritter and what he did,

00:54:08.230 --> 00:54:10.470
that book, those recordings.

00:54:10.470 --> 00:54:11.770
&gt;&gt; Derek Goldman: Right.

00:54:11.770 --> 00:54:14.650
It's my favorite, it's the
best baseball book, I think.

00:54:14.650 --> 00:54:15.950
It's a beautiful book.

00:54:15.950 --> 00:54:21.150
So, this is the third of our
readings, and it's, so Studs,

00:54:21.150 --> 00:54:23.210
as we've said, did not live

00:54:23.210 --> 00:54:25.470
to see the Cubs winning the
World Series, but he did live

00:54:25.470 --> 00:54:29.270
to see the White Sox win the
World Series which was a team,

00:54:29.270 --> 00:54:30.570
as you've heard a
little bit already,

00:54:30.570 --> 00:54:33.300
that in some ways was
closer to his heart

00:54:33.300 --> 00:54:35.570
and deeper in his heart.

00:54:35.570 --> 00:54:38.880
And, these, this last
one is kind of woven

00:54:38.880 --> 00:54:41.660
from some of Studs' writings.

00:54:41.660 --> 00:54:44.900
He was looked to around
that time to sort of comment

00:54:44.900 --> 00:54:47.660
on what was happening with
the White Sox and that sort

00:54:47.660 --> 00:54:49.950
of opened out as it
always did with Studs

00:54:49.950 --> 00:54:51.600
into some other commentary.

00:54:51.600 --> 00:54:55.100
So, this is from that,
from that period.

00:54:56.700 --> 00:54:58.540
&gt;&gt; David Strathairn: It's
a possibility the Cubs

00:54:58.540 --> 00:55:00.850
and the White Sox
in the World Series.

00:55:00.850 --> 00:55:03.710
The thought is overwhelming.

00:55:03.710 --> 00:55:07.270
It's happened before, and
you could look it up, 1906.

00:55:07.270 --> 00:55:08.750
The Sox won.

00:55:08.750 --> 00:55:12.320
Of all that has happened,
the Roaring '20s,

00:55:12.320 --> 00:55:16.080
the Great Depression, the war
against fascism, the Cold War,

00:55:16.080 --> 00:55:21.160
McCarthyism, the mad adventure
in southeast Asia, our own time

00:55:21.160 --> 00:55:22.960
of great bewilderment.

00:55:22.960 --> 00:55:24.360
The Cubs and the White Sox

00:55:24.360 --> 00:55:27.510
in the World Series would
be the most unimaginable.

00:55:27.510 --> 00:55:30.040
[ Laughter ]

00:55:30.040 --> 00:55:31.480
I'm working on my memoirs.

00:55:31.480 --> 00:55:32.950
It's the last thing I'll do

00:55:32.950 --> 00:55:35.520
if I can finish it
before I check out.

00:55:35.520 --> 00:55:39.840
I'm going to be 94 soon,
so if I make it a year,

00:55:39.840 --> 00:55:41.800
I've got it made.

00:55:41.800 --> 00:55:45.240
I was raised as a
Giants fan in New York.

00:55:45.240 --> 00:55:49.420
I was eight years old
when I came here in 1920.

00:55:49.420 --> 00:55:51.980
I was a John McGraw fan.

00:55:51.980 --> 00:55:54.750
John McGraw was for
blacks in baseball.

00:55:54.750 --> 00:55:56.050
You know that?

00:55:56.050 --> 00:56:00.550
He tried to pass off a
couple of blacks as Cubans.

00:56:00.550 --> 00:56:03.500
After a while, I
became a Sox fan.

00:56:03.500 --> 00:56:05.300
How could you not
root for a team

00:56:05.300 --> 00:56:11.450
that after the 1919 scandal was
so bad you had to root for them?

00:56:11.450 --> 00:56:15.850
Earl [inaudible], first base,
had a wooden leg almost.

00:56:15.850 --> 00:56:19.080
And, an outfielder
named Smeed Jolly.

00:56:19.080 --> 00:56:20.950
How could you not
root for a team

00:56:20.950 --> 00:56:24.280
with an outfielder
named Smeed Jolly?

00:56:25.670 --> 00:56:28.180
The Cubs have been
a legend for years.

00:56:28.180 --> 00:56:30.100
Nothing to do with baseball.

00:56:30.100 --> 00:56:32.250
You have to understand that.

00:56:32.250 --> 00:56:37.540
The Cubs' popularity had nothing
whatsoever to do with baseball.

00:56:37.540 --> 00:56:41.690
It's a place to come to,
as they say the air show is

00:56:41.690 --> 00:56:45.100
or the auto show or
the Art Institute.

00:56:45.100 --> 00:56:48.270
It's a place to be
at, and many have come

00:56:48.270 --> 00:56:50.900
from suburbs and nearby towns.

00:56:50.900 --> 00:56:53.310
It's not really baseball.

00:56:53.310 --> 00:56:57.760
It's a place to be at, and
we see that with the bimbos

00:56:57.760 --> 00:57:00.920
and the louts and
the Bud Lights.

00:57:02.090 --> 00:57:06.830
After the game, you ask
them, "Who did the Cubs play?

00:57:06.830 --> 00:57:09.430
What was the score?"

00:57:09.430 --> 00:57:11.300
They shake their heads.

00:57:11.300 --> 00:57:12.970
It's not about baseball.

00:57:12.970 --> 00:57:17.110
It's about having
been to a place to be.

00:57:17.110 --> 00:57:21.540
You're talking to an old
guy who's a curmudgeon.

00:57:21.540 --> 00:57:22.840
Was I an athlete?

00:57:22.840 --> 00:57:24.220
Oh, god, no.

00:57:24.220 --> 00:57:26.850
I was the worst athlete ever.

00:57:26.850 --> 00:57:30.080
I'd fall off bicycles.

00:57:30.080 --> 00:57:32.730
You know who was a great story?

00:57:32.730 --> 00:57:36.030
Mo Berg. Now, he could catch.

00:57:36.030 --> 00:57:39.970
Now, he was so-so,
but he was a linguist.

00:57:39.970 --> 00:57:43.250
He worked in the Army
to do some decoding.

00:57:43.250 --> 00:57:45.420
He could speak about
seven languages,

00:57:45.420 --> 00:57:50.630
so one of the writers wrote, "He
could speak in seven languages

00:57:50.630 --> 00:57:52.200
but couldn't catch in one."

00:57:52.200 --> 00:57:54.390
[ Laughter ]

00:57:54.390 --> 00:57:57.670
Now, I don't want to glorify the
old days because they weren't

00:57:57.670 --> 00:58:00.970
that good either, but when
you went to see the Sox,

00:58:00.970 --> 00:58:03.420
at least it was a ballgame.

00:58:03.420 --> 00:58:07.350
I'm not saying Sox fans
are brighter than Cub fans.

00:58:07.350 --> 00:58:08.770
They're not.

00:58:08.770 --> 00:58:10.340
Well, neither one is.

00:58:10.340 --> 00:58:12.600
[ Laughter ]

00:58:12.600 --> 00:58:15.030
I'll never forget this.

00:58:15.030 --> 00:58:18.390
I was sitting with Bill Veeck in
the Bard's room, the dining room

00:58:18.390 --> 00:58:20.300
at the old Comiskey Park.

00:58:20.300 --> 00:58:21.810
And, it was about two weeks

00:58:21.810 --> 00:58:25.150
after he hired Larry
Doby as manager.

00:58:25.150 --> 00:58:28.200
Remember, he had Larry
as the first black player

00:58:28.200 --> 00:58:31.580
for the Indians, and
then, he managed the Sox.

00:58:31.580 --> 00:58:35.570
It was two weeks, two weeks, and
the Sox were losing more games

00:58:35.570 --> 00:58:37.220
than they were winning.

00:58:37.220 --> 00:58:40.880
So, there's a call, and
he answers the call.

00:58:40.880 --> 00:58:45.810
He's looking at me and
saying, "Oh, Mrs. Meyerhoff,"

00:58:45.810 --> 00:58:47.950
or whatever her name was.

00:58:47.950 --> 00:58:51.390
"You think I should
fire Larry Doby.

00:58:51.390 --> 00:58:52.820
It's only two weeks.

00:58:52.820 --> 00:58:56.320
We've only played
about ten games.

00:58:56.320 --> 00:58:58.180
Oh, oh, no.

00:58:58.180 --> 00:59:00.900
I know. It's not race."

00:59:00.900 --> 00:59:03.460
And, he raises his
eyes to the ceiling.

00:59:03.460 --> 00:59:05.720
"Oh, it's not race at all.

00:59:05.720 --> 00:59:09.120
No, I realize that."

00:59:09.120 --> 00:59:14.350
A 1919 Black Sox scandal,
Buck Weaver, third baseman,

00:59:14.350 --> 00:59:16.540
did not take part in it.

00:59:16.540 --> 00:59:19.120
He didn't inform
on the other guys.

00:59:19.120 --> 00:59:20.420
The eighth guy kicked

00:59:20.420 --> 00:59:23.660
out of should have been
Sox owner Charles Comiskey,

00:59:23.660 --> 00:59:26.320
the way he exploited
the players.

00:59:26.320 --> 00:59:29.960
It made them a natural for
a guy like Arnold Rothstein,

00:59:29.960 --> 00:59:35.190
the gambler who fixed
the 1919 World Series.

00:59:35.190 --> 00:59:39.600
I had a friend, 91 like me,
who wants to live to 2008

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:42.350
because he thinks the Cubs
and the White Sox may meet

00:59:42.350 --> 00:59:45.570
in the World Series to
celebrate the 100th anniversary

00:59:45.570 --> 00:59:48.220
of the Cubs winning the series.

00:59:48.220 --> 00:59:50.570
At least we can dream.

00:59:50.570 --> 00:59:52.880
It's over the rainbow.

00:59:52.880 --> 00:59:55.650
We're all Judy Garlands.

00:59:55.650 --> 00:59:57.990
Do saucers fly?

00:59:57.990 --> 01:00:00.510
Do fiddlers play on rooftops?

01:00:00.510 --> 01:00:11.400
[ Applause ]

01:00:11.400 --> 01:00:12.700
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus: So,
let's take some questions.

01:00:12.700 --> 01:00:14.690
All right.

01:00:14.690 --> 01:00:15.990
Do we want to pass it?

01:00:15.990 --> 01:00:17.290
We don't have a mic
we can pass to.

01:00:17.290 --> 01:00:18.590
Okay. We'll repeat
the question, then.

01:00:18.590 --> 01:00:19.890
Great.

01:00:19.890 --> 01:00:21.340
&gt;&gt; Thank you all.

01:00:21.340 --> 01:00:26.080
I just want to put in a plug

01:00:26.080 --> 01:00:32.820
for [inaudible] who's not just
a reporter, but he wrote some

01:00:32.820 --> 01:00:39.060
of the most marvelous
stories about baseball ever.

01:00:39.060 --> 01:00:41.570
And, he's largely
forgotten now, unfortunately.

01:00:41.570 --> 01:00:42.870
But, especially [inaudible].

01:00:42.870 --> 01:00:44.170
&gt;&gt; Derek Goldman: Thank you.

01:00:44.170 --> 01:00:45.470
&gt;&gt; John Sayles: Yeah,
Ring, Jr., his son got,

01:00:45.470 --> 01:00:46.770
I got to know a little bit.

01:00:46.770 --> 01:00:48.070
He, we invited him to the set.

01:00:48.070 --> 01:00:49.370
And, I said, and
there was a scene

01:00:49.370 --> 01:00:50.670
where I was playing
Ring Lardner,

01:00:50.670 --> 01:00:54.410
and I asked him afterwards
what it was

01:00:54.410 --> 01:00:56.700
like to see somebody
play his father.

01:00:56.700 --> 01:00:59.010
And, he said, "Uncomfortably
familiar."

01:00:59.010 --> 01:01:00.310
[ Laughter ]

01:01:00.310 --> 01:01:01.610
Which I took as a compliment.

01:01:01.610 --> 01:01:03.480
But, he was a great writer.

01:01:03.480 --> 01:01:05.190
He never quite wrote novels.

01:01:05.190 --> 01:01:06.490
He wrote short stories.

01:01:06.490 --> 01:01:13.650
He wrote musicals, and he was
so, he was a friend of most

01:01:13.650 --> 01:01:18.240
of those ball players, and he
was, but he was a straight guy.

01:01:18.240 --> 01:01:23.850
He was so troubled by the
immorality of it and then, just,

01:01:23.850 --> 01:01:28.860
he felt like he had
let down their public.

01:01:28.860 --> 01:01:31.270
And, he always was
very uncomfortable

01:01:31.270 --> 01:01:34.730
with this relationship with
Comiskey and free drinks

01:01:34.730 --> 01:01:36.030
for all the reporters.

01:01:36.030 --> 01:01:41.400
And, some of that, the story
about how he developed his style

01:01:41.400 --> 01:01:43.940
of writing because he was,
Hemingway was a big fan

01:01:43.940 --> 01:01:47.480
of Ring Lardner's, and
one of the things he liked

01:01:47.480 --> 01:01:49.570
about Ring Lardner is
he felt like he was one

01:01:49.570 --> 01:01:52.610
of the most successful
and few American writers

01:01:52.610 --> 01:01:56.140
after Mark Twain who
wrote in vernacular.

01:01:56.140 --> 01:01:59.300
And, he started writing in
this voice that you hear,

01:01:59.300 --> 01:02:02.530
and you know me now and
some of these other stories.

01:02:02.530 --> 01:02:05.510
He traveled with both the Cubs
and the White Sox and went

01:02:05.510 --> 01:02:06.980
on some of their
road games with them.

01:02:06.980 --> 01:02:09.510
And, he'd be on the train
with them and stuff like that.

01:02:09.510 --> 01:02:12.290
And, you notice that he'd
stay in the same hotel.

01:02:12.290 --> 01:02:14.620
There was this one
player who always sat next

01:02:14.620 --> 01:02:16.780
to him on the, at breakfast.

01:02:16.780 --> 01:02:19.950
And, he started to realize
there's something weird.

01:02:19.950 --> 01:02:22.800
He always orders what I order.

01:02:22.800 --> 01:02:26.210
Exactly. And, he started
ordering some kind of, you know,

01:02:26.210 --> 01:02:28.280
exotic things, and the guy
would order the same thing.

01:02:28.280 --> 01:02:32.500
And, then, he realized
the guy's illiterate.

01:02:32.500 --> 01:02:36.010
And, I'm a big breakfast
eater, and he just figures,

01:02:36.010 --> 01:02:37.310
well, I'll read the menu.

01:02:37.310 --> 01:02:38.610
Oh, I'll have the same he does.

01:02:38.610 --> 01:02:40.960
Or, I just repeat the thing.

01:02:40.960 --> 01:02:47.150
So, it kind of was obvious
the guy thought, well,

01:02:47.150 --> 01:02:49.890
Ring must know that, but we're
not going to talk about it.

01:02:49.890 --> 01:02:52.440
And, one day, the guy came
to him and said, "Ring,

01:02:52.440 --> 01:02:57.540
I want to play a joke on my
wife, and I'm going to tell her

01:02:57.540 --> 01:02:59.360
that I'm learning how to type.

01:02:59.360 --> 01:03:00.780
But, I don't really
know how to type.

01:03:00.780 --> 01:03:03.620
So, I'm going to dictate letters
to you, and you type them

01:03:03.620 --> 01:03:05.650
up like I wrote them."

01:03:05.650 --> 01:03:08.690
And, he realized the guy misses
his wife and wants to write

01:03:08.690 --> 01:03:11.070
to her, and he can't do it
because he's illiterate.

01:03:11.070 --> 01:03:14.090
And so, he went through
this charade, and you know,

01:03:14.090 --> 01:03:17.130
every couple days, the guy
would dictate, and the guy was,

01:03:17.130 --> 01:03:18.800
you know, not very educated.

01:03:18.800 --> 01:03:21.310
And, he made a lot
of grammar mistakes.

01:03:21.310 --> 01:03:24.620
And, Ring said, "I'm going
to spell like he could spell

01:03:24.620 --> 01:03:26.450
if he could spell at all."

01:03:26.450 --> 01:03:30.500
And, that was where that
voice originally came from was

01:03:30.500 --> 01:03:33.540
from this illiterate
guy dictating to Ring

01:03:33.540 --> 01:03:36.610
and him saying, "This guy's a
great storyteller, but I'm going

01:03:36.610 --> 01:03:39.530
to tell it in his voice."

