01:03:52.440 --> 01:03:54.950
&gt;&gt; I was thrilled
that the footage

01:03:54.950 --> 01:04:02.490
of the 1919 World Series
surfaced [inaudible].

01:04:02.490 --> 01:04:10.430
But, I was wondering what other
audio visual record if any

01:04:10.430 --> 01:04:15.080
of the 1919 series exists.

01:04:15.080 --> 01:04:16.990
&gt;&gt; John Sayles: There was
very, very little at the time,

01:04:16.990 --> 01:04:19.970
and there was, it was
mostly in news reels.

01:04:19.970 --> 01:04:24.000
I have to figure in 1919,
you know, in the movie,

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:26.860
you see people listening
to crystal sets.

01:04:26.860 --> 01:04:29.080
So, radio hadn't
even really started.

01:04:29.080 --> 01:04:33.480
A couple years from then, for
the first many, many years,

01:04:33.480 --> 01:04:36.630
ballgames were not
broadcast live.

01:04:36.630 --> 01:04:39.950
It was two guys getting a ticker
tape, and there's famous stories

01:04:39.950 --> 01:04:42.420
of Ronald Reagan when
other guys, when he did it

01:04:42.420 --> 01:04:45.410
when the ticker tape would break
down, they'd, like, invent,

01:04:45.410 --> 01:04:48.760
well, the manager's going out
to the mound again, and it looks

01:04:48.760 --> 01:04:50.880
like it may rain, and
they're, you know.

01:04:50.880 --> 01:04:52.180
And, they'd have to stall.

01:04:52.180 --> 01:04:54.410
And, they would have sound
effects for a homerun

01:04:54.410 --> 01:04:56.390
and cheers and things like that.

01:04:56.390 --> 01:05:00.420
So, there just wasn't
that much film,

01:05:00.420 --> 01:05:05.840
and it came from the archives of
the news reels, and apparently,

01:05:05.840 --> 01:05:10.150
there was this stuff, you know,
up frozen under a, you know,

01:05:10.150 --> 01:05:13.360
a building that had been a movie
theater or something like that

01:05:13.360 --> 01:05:14.660
or had been converted

01:05:14.660 --> 01:05:16.620
into a movie theater
whenever the film got

01:05:16.620 --> 01:05:18.530
up during the gold rush.

01:05:18.530 --> 01:05:23.300
And, there's some interesting,
including this bizarre thing

01:05:23.300 --> 01:05:29.310
that somebody flew a plane over
game two and dropped a dummy

01:05:29.310 --> 01:05:31.020
of a ball player from it.

01:05:31.020 --> 01:05:32.320
And, people thought,
"Oh, my god.

01:05:32.320 --> 01:05:33.620
He's going to die."

01:05:33.620 --> 01:05:36.110
You know, and they actually
were warned about that,

01:05:36.110 --> 01:05:38.030
and so that was one of
the things that they got.

01:05:38.030 --> 01:05:41.680
But, it was amazing to see that
after we had made the movie.

01:05:41.680 --> 01:05:42.980
And, we felt like, geez,

01:05:42.980 --> 01:05:44.670
our uniforms look
really pretty good.

01:05:44.670 --> 01:05:47.060
[ Laughter ]

01:05:47.060 --> 01:05:48.360
&gt;&gt; Matthew Barton:
Just a general remark

01:05:48.360 --> 01:05:51.700
about what survives
of early radio.

01:05:51.700 --> 01:05:58.040
Even if games had been broadcast
in 1919 or in the 1920s,

01:05:58.040 --> 01:06:00.200
we probably wouldn't
have anything of them

01:06:00.200 --> 01:06:04.110
because very little radio
from before 1935 survives.

01:06:04.110 --> 01:06:07.950
The 1934 World Series does,
recordings of that do exist,

01:06:07.950 --> 01:06:12.270
but there was no easy way to
record radio at any length more

01:06:12.270 --> 01:06:15.140
than a few minutes
until about 1935.

01:06:15.140 --> 01:06:17.540
And, from that point
on, we do have a lot,

01:06:17.540 --> 01:06:21.750
but there's hardly any radio
survives from before 1935.

01:06:21.750 --> 01:06:23.050
&gt;&gt; Tony Macalus:
And, I'll just say

01:06:23.050 --> 01:06:25.210
if you want an internal
experience what it was

01:06:25.210 --> 01:06:28.620
like to be a nine year old kid
watching the 1919 White Sox,

