[ Inaudible Comment ]

01:14:27.040 --> 01:14:28.590
&gt;&gt; John Sayles: You know, for
me, people are always saying,

01:14:28.590 --> 01:14:31.290
you know, you think Joe Jackson
should be in the Hall of Fame?

01:14:31.290 --> 01:14:34.430
You know, and I always, you
know, I feel like the same thing

01:14:34.430 --> 01:14:37.140
with Sammy Sosa and
all of these things.

01:14:37.140 --> 01:14:40.810
When Roger Maris
first, you know,

01:14:40.810 --> 01:14:43.440
it looked like he was
going to, you know,

01:14:43.440 --> 01:14:46.020
break Babe Ruth's record and
when Hank Aaron finally did,

01:14:46.020 --> 01:14:50.210
you know, they put an asterisk
next to his record saying, well,

01:14:50.210 --> 01:14:51.660
he played in more games.

01:14:51.660 --> 01:14:54.270
And, it was a different game
and everything like that.

01:14:54.270 --> 01:14:58.220
And, I always feel like
there should be, you know,

01:14:58.220 --> 01:15:00.270
whether it's O.J.
Simpson or anything else.

01:15:00.270 --> 01:15:01.570
You don't take their
records away.

01:15:01.570 --> 01:15:05.180
You put as asterisk
next to them, you know,

01:15:05.180 --> 01:15:07.300
so Pete Rose, you know.

01:15:07.300 --> 01:15:09.160
Great player.

01:15:09.160 --> 01:15:13.220
Personally, he's
got the asterisk.

01:15:13.220 --> 01:15:14.850
For me, one of the
fascinating things

01:15:14.850 --> 01:15:18.590
about the story was it
was about corruption.

01:15:18.590 --> 01:15:22.500
And, it reminded me originally
of "All the Presidents Men",

01:15:22.500 --> 01:15:25.820
of how people become corrupted
and corrupt each other

01:15:25.820 --> 01:15:30.660
and how many conspiracies
don't work.

01:15:30.660 --> 01:15:32.350
And, the ones that
don't work are the ones

01:15:32.350 --> 01:15:34.100
where the people are
a little bit ashamed

01:15:34.100 --> 01:15:35.400
of what they're doing.

01:15:35.400 --> 01:15:37.710
They don't have enough meetings.

01:15:37.710 --> 01:15:42.530
So, the [inaudible] like two
mass meetings about are we in

01:15:42.530 --> 01:15:43.890
or are we out and
what we're doing.

01:15:43.890 --> 01:15:45.610
So, there were guys who
thought they were only going

01:15:45.610 --> 01:15:48.270
to throw one game who
were saying, "What?

01:15:48.270 --> 01:15:50.940
Are we throwing this one or
are we winning this one?"

01:15:50.940 --> 01:15:53.300
Because they didn't
have enough meetings.

01:15:53.300 --> 01:15:57.640
And, I think what's fascinating,
you know, about it is, yes,

01:15:57.640 --> 01:16:01.550
it was a labor situation,
but they did, also,

01:16:01.550 --> 01:16:03.600
sell their own teammates out.

01:16:03.600 --> 01:16:04.970
They didn't let them in on it,

01:16:04.970 --> 01:16:06.600
and their teammates
were trying to win.

01:16:06.600 --> 01:16:08.210
So, it's a, you know, it's a,

01:16:08.210 --> 01:16:10.240
you can't really make
heroes of these guys.

01:16:10.240 --> 01:16:12.580
And, some of them,
like Joe Jackson,

01:16:12.580 --> 01:16:14.100
were just brow beat into it.

01:16:14.100 --> 01:16:16.100
You don't want to
be who, you know,

01:16:16.100 --> 01:16:18.160
messes it all up, do you, Joe?

01:16:18.160 --> 01:16:20.850
And, you know, he was
afraid of these guys.

01:16:20.850 --> 01:16:22.670
And then, others did it
because they were greedy.

01:16:22.670 --> 01:16:25.300
Some did it because they
felt like they were right

01:16:25.300 --> 01:16:26.920
on the verge of being
out of [inaudible].

01:16:26.920 --> 01:16:31.720
But, how people become corrupted
and accept a bad situation

01:16:31.720 --> 01:16:34.830
and don't fight against
it in the right way.

01:16:34.830 --> 01:16:38.610
I think that's a, you know,
it's a nice little microcosm.

01:16:38.610 --> 01:16:41.730
Just like it was, you know,
with the Brooklyn Dodgers

01:16:41.730 --> 01:16:44.070
when Jackie Robinson,
you know, played.

01:16:44.070 --> 01:16:46.210
There were guys who said, "Well,
I'm not playing with him."

01:16:46.210 --> 01:16:49.210
And, they ended up being, like,
"He's my teammate, and I'll,

01:16:49.210 --> 01:16:52.520
if you mess with him, I'm
going to punch you out."

01:16:52.520 --> 01:16:57.650
You know, human beings are,
this is the essence of Studs.

01:16:57.650 --> 01:17:02.920
Human beings are strange and
wonderful creatures, and you,

01:17:02.920 --> 01:17:04.690
and everyone's an individual.

01:17:04.690 --> 01:17:08.650
And, you can't just say, he's
a, you know, Hispanic American

01:17:08.650 --> 01:17:12.230
in his 30s and therefore
he thinks or is this.

01:17:12.230 --> 01:17:14.940
You got to talk to the
guy and bring it out.

01:17:14.940 --> 01:17:17.510
And, everybody's
got their own story.

